accesses.location: THERE IS A COUNTY OWNED ACCESS ON THE SOUTH SHORE OF THE LAKE.

surveys.narrative: Black bullhead were the most abundant species present during the survey. Most were small with a few over 10 inches. Bluegill were abundant with one-fifth of the fish of acceptable size to anglers. Black crappie numbers were moderate, higher than in previous nettings. Fish were small, less than 9 inches in length. Yellow perch were moderate in number with fish under 8 inches. Previous nettings found low numbers of perch. Northern pike were fair in number with several fish over 24 inches. Largemouth bass numbers appear to be moderate with numbers of young fish captured. Electrofishing was not done to assess the adult population. Yellow bullhead numbers were fair with a tenth of the fish over 12 inches. One carp was captured.

Lake Wabasso is a small lake covering 46.4 acres. A small boat access is located on the south shore in the county park. Shore access is limited to the boat access area. The most abundant species of fish present in the lake are bluegills. Although they are plentiful they are small. The average size is only 5.3 inches in length. Only 5% of the bluegills sampled were over 7 inches. Northern pike were found in average abundance and averaged 22.8 inches in length. Black crappies were sampled in low numbers and small size. Only one black crappie exceeding 10 inches in length was sampled. Largemouth bass arenot sampled effectively in trap nets or gill nets. This is reflected in the low numbers captured in this survey. Lake Wabasso has had a history of good largemouth bass fishing.

Based on net catches, local medians and the range of values for 50% of the catches around the local median, the following species exhibit higher populations than expected for area lakes: northern pike. Black crappie are low in numbers. Black, brown, and yellow bullhead, bluegill, pumpkinseed, and hybrid sunfish all appear present in expected numbers for lakes in this area. Yellow perch, taken in low numbers in 1975 were not taken in 1980. Northern pike numbers are significantly higher in 1980 than in 1975. The II annulus fish were most abundant which corresponds to the 1978 stocking. Their growth rate was fast. Both black crappie and bluegill numbers appear to be lower than in 1975.

Bluegill are present in numbers greatly exceeding state and local medians while northern pike and all three species of bullheads are present in numbers somewhat above average. Largemouth bass and pumpkinseed numbers are about average and black crappie, white sucker, and carp are present in below median numbers. Bluegill trapnet catches are up dramatically from 1980 (612/lift vs. 32/lift). All bullhead species were also caught in much higher numbers than in 1980. Northern pike and black crappie were caught in numbers similar to 1980.

As compared with the statewide figures, the net catches are as follows: (1) There were above average catches of northern pike and bluegills; (2) Near average catches of pumpkinseeds and green sunfish; and (3) Below average catches of common suckers, brown bullheads, yellow bullheads, and black crappies. The growth rate of the northern pike was above average, the growth rate of the pumpkinseeds was about average, and the growth rate of the bluegills was below average when compared with the statewide figures.Wabasso Lake covers a total area of 46.4 acres, has a maximum depth of 66 feet, and a median depth of 9 feet. About 60% of the lake area is shallower than 15 feet. There are no inlet or outlet streams present. The bottom soil along 75% of the shoreline is composed of muck, and sand overlaid with silt is common along the remaining shoreline.The Secchi disc reading of 18 feet indicated that the water in Wabasso Lake is quite clear and colorless. Chemical analysis of the lake water indicated that Wabasso Lake is a hard-water lake, and dissolved oxygen testing indicated that during the summer months the dissolved oxygen content below the thermocline is too low to support warm-water fish. Submerged aquatic plants were very abundant to a depth of about 10 feet, and emergent aquatic plants were moderately abundant along the shoreline at the time of the survey.About 78% of the total number of fish taken in the test nets were bluegills. Northern pike were also taken in good numbers in the test nets. The growth rate of the northern pike was above average, and the growth rate of the bluegills was below average when compared with the statewide figures. The shoreline seining indicated good natural reproduction in 1959 for largemouth bass. Local residents reported that summer angling for panfish and winter darkhouse spearing for northern pike has been good during the past years. There is a county-owned public access to the lake and a picnic area along the south shoreline of the lake.

Lake Wabbaso is a 46-acre Bass-Bluegill lake located in Ramsey County where Bluegill and Largemouth Bass are the primary management species, and Northern Pike are a secondary management species. Bluegills were the most abundant species sampled in Lake Wabasso, although catches were significantly lower than in previous surveys. Bluegills were sampled at 9.63 fish/net in the trap nets, down from 54.33 fish/net in 2005 and 77.22 fish/net in 2000. The avergae numer of Bluegill in the trapnets was between the 1st and 2nd quartiles for class 30 lakes. The average size Bluegill sampled in 2015 was 6.29 inches with individuals up to 8.15 inches. Black Crappies were sampled in trap nets at a rate of 1.5 fish/net, and averaged 7.86 inches with individuals up to 10.5 inches. 33% of sampled Black Crappies were 9 inches or larger. Anglers fishing Lake Wabasso should find fewer but larger Bluegills than in 2005.

Night time electrofishing sampled 13 Largemouth Bass at a rate of 18.57 fish/hr of on-time. This was the first time that night time electrofishing has been conducted on Lake Wabasso. Mean length of Largemouth Bass sampled in 2015 was 11.75 inches with bass up to 15 inches.

Northern Pike were sampled at 8.5 fish/gillnet, which is above the 3rd quartile for class 30 lakes. The average length of Northern Pike sampled in gillnets in 2015 was 18.8 inches and the largest Northern Pike was 22.48 inches. Northern Pike in Lake Wabasso appear to be more abundant but of smaller size than in 2005 and 2000.

Northern pike, carp, black bullhead, and yellow perch were each below their respective statewide medians in number and pounds per set. Brown bullhead, pumpkinseed, bluegill, and black crappie were each above their respective statewide medians in number and pounds per set.

Northern pike were sampled in average numbers and exhibited average growth. Recruitment was poor, with no fish younger than IV sampled. Bluegills were very abundant, but were of average size. White sucker, black bullhead, yellow bullhead, hybrid sunfish, pumpkinseed, black crappie, and yellow perch were sampled in low numbers.

Bluegills are abundant in Lake Wabasso. Lengths ranged up to 7 inches, but most were between 5 and 6.5 inches. Northern pike were sampled in moderate numbers, but were small - between 20 and 25 inches. Largemouth bass were sampled up to 16.5 inches long, with good numbers between 12 and 16 inches. Black crappie are not abundant, but a large proportion of the catch was between 8 and 11 inches. Pumpkinseed and hybrid sunfish were sampled in moderate numbers. Yellow perch and bullheads were sampled in low numbers.
